==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sward
<hw>Sward</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS. <ets>sweard</ets>
skin, covering; akin to OFries. <ets>swarge</ets>, D. <ets>zwoord</ets>,
G. <ets>schwarte</ets>, Icel. <ets>sv⟦oum⟧r<?/r</ets> skin, sward of the
earth.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Skin; covering.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The grassy surface of land; that part of the soil
which is filled with the roots of grass; turf.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>sward</qex> was trim as any garden lawn.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sward pork</b></col>, <cd>bacon in large fitches.</cd>
<mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sward</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sward
<hw>Sward</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Swarded</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Swarding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To produce sward upon; to cover,
or be covered, with sward.</def> <rj><au>Mortimer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

